er.blogspot.co.uk/">Simon Johnson</a> as this was where the two of us ended up after a fun&nbsp;</span>afternoon<span style="-webkit-text-stroke-width: initial;">&nbsp;of drinking not long before he died). And so I sit with a glass of </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/pentrichbrewingco" style="-webkit-text-stroke-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); -webkit-text-stroke-width: initial;">Pentrich</a><span style="-webkit-text-stroke-width: initial;"> Citra IPA (hazy, plumpish in its fruitiness and rapier-like in its bitterness) and there is a joy in my heart as I note the hooks that hang beneath the brow of the scuffed, dark brown bar. It?s a habit I have, a tradition perhaps, or maybe a nervous tic, but all too often when I find myself standing (or sitting) at a bar, elbow in a puddle of spilt beer and crushed crisps, I always put my hand beneath the brow and search for a hook, usually something on which I can hang my rucksack (just like the chap has done in the photo). It?s a neat little aid, a helping hand to the drinker, perhaps even a link with the kind of imagined past that some pubs are so adept at.&nbsp;</span></span></span></div><div style="-webkit-text-stroke-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); -webkit-text-stroke-width: initial; line-height: normal;"><br /></div>";s:4:"link";s:82:"http://maltworms.blogspot.com/2017/08/the-hanging-hooks-of-pubs-imagined-past.html";s:6:"author";s:42:"noreply@blogger.com (Adrian Tierney-Jones)";s:7:"summary";s:2382:"<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"><a href="https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-FUzDibi5Dec/WaacSLXpvII/AAAAAAAADQo/7BMxUOtNL3QLZxrDacLDvdUksMzhYoAbgCLcBGAs/s1600/IMG_3277.JPG" imageanchor="1" style="clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;"><img border="0" data-original-height="1600" data-original-width="1200" height="320" src="https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-FUzDibi5Dec/WaacSLXpvII/AAAAAAAADQo/7BMxUOtNL3QLZxrDacLDvdUksMzhYoAbgCLcBGAs/s320/IMG_3277.JPG" width="240" /></a></div><div style="line-heigh